Herein, we propose a hydronium-ion battery, in which H3O+ is used as charge carrier to couple the reversible quinone/hydroquinone redox reaction in a pyrene-4,5,9,10-tetraone (PTO)-based anode and the reversible Mn2+/MnO2 conversion reaction in a carbon-based cathode. Figure 1 illustrates the structure of the hydronium-ion battery, which involves a PTO-based anode and a graphite felt (GF) electrode (that serves as both substrate and current collector for cathode) in an acid electrolyte containing Mn2+ (i.e., 2 M MnSO4 + 2 M H2SO4). On charge, the Mn2+ in electrolyte is oxidized into MnO2 precipitate on GF electrode with generation of H3O+ (Eq. 1), and simultaneously H3O+ in the electrolyte is stored by PTO to form hydroquinone (HQ) through the reaction shown in Eq. 2. Electrons obviously transfer from cathode to anode through external circuit. The discharge reverses the charge process. The overall charge/discharge operation mechanism is as follows:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
